Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Halve, peel, and dice
@yellow onion{1}(diced). Mince or grate @garlic{4%cloves}(minced). Halve
@grape tomatoes{8%ounce} lengthwise. Strip @thyme{1/4%ounce}(leaves stripped from
stems) and discard stems.

Bring 5 cups water to a boil in a large #pot. Meanwhile, heat a large drizzle of
@olive oil{2%teaspoon} in another large #pot over medium heat. Add onion and
garlic. Cook until softened, about ~{3%minutes}, stirring. Season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

Increase heat to medium-high and add thyme, 2 TBSP @tomato paste{1%unit}, ½ tsp
@sugar{1/2%teaspoon}, and @fresh pork chorizo{12%ounce} to same #pot. Break up
meat into pieces with a #spatula or #wooden spoon. Cook until chorizo is just
starting to brown, ~{4-5%minutes}.

While chorizo cooks, toss tomatoes, a large drizzle of olive oil, and a pinch of
salt and pepper on a #baking sheet. Roast in #oven until beginning to burst,
about ~{10%minutes}.

Meanwhile, add @orzo pasta{12%ounce} to #pot and stir to combine. Add boiling
water and @veggie stock concentrate{2%unit} and bring to a simmer. Let bubble
until orzo is al dente, about ~{12%minutes}, stirring frequently.

> TIP: If liquid evaporates before orzo is done, add water 1/4 cup at a time
> and continue cooking.

When orzo is al dente, stir in @mozzarella cheese{1%cup}, tomatoes, and half
the @parmesan cheese{1/2%cup}. Lay @spinach{5%ounce} on top and cover #pot.
Remove from heat and let sit ~{3%minutes} to allow spinach to steam. Stir
spinach into orzo mixture. Divide between plates and sprinkle with remaining
parmesan.